# LiVEiT® Icon Usage

Icons play an important role within the LiVEiT® Framework by helping users recognise actions, navigate interfaces and understand information quickly.

Icons should support the user experience by providing clear visual cues without replacing descriptive text where it is needed.

---

# Design Principles

Official LiVEiT® icons should be:

* Simple
* Consistent
* Recognisable
* Accessible
* Scalable

Icons should complement the interface rather than dominate it.

---

# Style

All official icons should maintain a consistent visual style.

Recommended characteristics include:

* Clean geometric shapes
* Consistent line weights
* Balanced proportions
* Minimal visual complexity
* Clear silhouettes

Mixing multiple icon styles within the same interface should be avoided.

---

# Consistency

Icons representing similar actions should appear visually related.

Maintain consistency in:

* Stroke width
* Corner radius
* Visual weight
* Perspective
* Alignment

Consistency improves recognition and reduces cognitive load.

---

# Size

Icons should remain clear at all supported sizes.

Typical recommendations include:

| Usage               | Suggested Size |
| ------------------- | -------------- |
| Navigation          | 20–24 px       |
| Buttons             | 20–24 px       |
| Toolbars            | 24 px          |
| Lists               | 16–20 px       |
| Large Feature Icons | 32–64 px       |

Icons should always scale proportionally.

---

# Colour

Icons should use official LiVEiT® colours where appropriate.

Recommended usage includes:

* Neutral colours for standard interface controls.
* Brand colours for emphasis.
* White icons on dark backgrounds.
* Dark icons on light backgrounds.

Colour should never reduce legibility.

---

# Filled and Outlined Icons

Both filled and outlined icons may be used.

However, individual interfaces should remain visually consistent by selecting one primary style for similar controls.

Avoid mixing filled and outlined versions of the same icon within a single interface unless there is a deliberate functional distinction.

---

# Alignment

Icons should align consistently with surrounding text and interface elements.

Maintain:

* Equal padding
* Consistent spacing
* Balanced visual positioning
* Proper vertical alignment

Good alignment contributes to a professional appearance.

---

# Accessibility

Icons should never be the only method used to communicate meaning.

Where appropriate:

* Pair icons with descriptive labels.
* Provide accessible names for assistive technologies.
* Ensure sufficient colour contrast.
* Avoid relying solely on colour to indicate status.

Accessibility should be considered throughout the design process.

---

# Official LiVEiT® Icons

Official LiVEiT® icons supplied with the framework should not be modified.

Do not:

* Stretch icons.
* Rotate icons unnecessarily.
* Change proportions.
* Apply unofficial colours.
* Add visual effects that alter the intended appearance.

Use only official assets provided within the repository.

---

# Circle Icons

The LiVEiT® circular navigation system is a defining feature of the framework.

Each circle represents a specific functional area within the LiVEiT® methodology and should retain its official colour, structure and visual identity.

These icons should remain consistent across:

* Websites
* Mobile applications
* Desktop software
* Documentation
* Presentations

Maintaining consistency reinforces recognition throughout the LiVEiT® ecosystem.

---

# Future Development

Additional icons may be introduced as the framework expands.

New icons should follow the same visual principles established throughout this guide to ensure they integrate seamlessly with the existing icon library.
